The paper deals with a geometric optimization problem involving points in Euclidean space, which suggests that it could belong to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The problem also involves a supply function and transportation maps, which suggests that it could belong to the discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. The algorithmic approach and time complexity suggest that it could belong to the data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The use of Euclidean distances and optimization criteria suggest that it could belong to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Finally, the mention of real-valued supplies and spread suggests that it could belong to the numerical analysis (cs.NA) sub-category.
